  "original_title": "Sri Lanka Treasury bills close at 29.00/30-pct, guidance peg flat",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka Treasury bills close at 29.00/30-pct, guidance peg flat",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT  \u2013 Sri Lanka\u2019s 3-month Treasury bills closed at 29.00/30 percent after an auction while a guidance peg was hardly changed Wednesday, dealers said.",
        "There are growing fears in the market that dollars bond holders will force a second hair cut on rupee Treasuries, who are have suffered a close to 50 percent hair cut on depreciation already and are paying higher inflated taxes to meet state spending, market participants said.",
        "At Wednesday\u2019s Treasuries auction yield rose over 400 basis points across maturities with weighted average yield topping 28 percent.",
        "In the secondary market, market was active in thin trade, dealers said.",
        "\u201cThe Market is currently waiting for the monetary policy announcement on Thursday,\u201d a dealer said.",
        "In the secondary market three-month bill closed at 29.00/30 percent on Wednesday, up from 24.75/25.00 percent Tuesday, indicating cut-off above the rate.",
        "The one-year bill closed at 29.00/30 percent on Wednesday up from 24.75/25.30 percent a day earlier.",
        "A bond maturing on 01.06.2025 was quoted at 24.00/25.15 percent on Wednesday, up from 24.00/25.00 Tuesday.",
        "A guidance peg announced by Sri Lanka\u2019s central bank for interbank transactions dropped three cents to 359.82 against the US dollar on July 06 from the previous 359.79 on July 05.",
        "Sri Lanka commercial banks offered dollars for telegraphic transfers at rates between 366.79 and 370.00 for small transactions on July 05, steady from Tuesday, commercial bank data showed.",
        "Banks offered to buy inward remittances at 356.50 -359.00 rupees, also steady from the previous day."
      ],
